1 Introduction - Dataset 1

In this project, a total of 3 data sets will be examined. These datasets include social issues. Each dataset contains year information. Using this yearâs information, the impact of the pandemic on individual issues will be mentioned.

The first data set includes the support of hot meals, soup, pita and food to people living in Ä°zmir. It is a matter of curiosity whether these aids increase during the pandemic.

4 Confidance Intervals - Dataset 1

4.1 Confidance Interval of TOPLAM_YARDIM

sample.mean <- mean(mydata$TOPLAM_YARDIM)
sample.n <- length(mydata$TOPLAM_YARDIM)
sample.sd <- sd(mydata$TOPLAM_YARDIM)
sample.se <- sample.sd/sqrt(sample.n)
alpha = 0.05
degrees.freedom = sample.n - 1
t.score = qt(p=alpha/2, df=degrees.freedom,lower.tail=F)
margin.error <- t.score * sample.se
lower.bound <- sample.mean - margin.error
upper.bound <- sample.mean + margin.error
print(c(lower.bound,upper.bound))
## [1] 174449.7 196169.4

As a result of the calculations, it was observed that the confidence intervals were 174449.7 and 196169.4.

4.2 Confidance Interval Between Years

ggplot(mydata, aes(factor(YIL), TOPLAM_YARDIM, fill=YIL)) +

When we look at the graph above, it is observed that the confidence interval of the aids in 2020 is much higher than the others. More consistent information can be provided with years other than 2020.

6 Hypothesis Tests - Dataset 1

6.1 Are there significant difference between mean TOPLAM_YARDIM of 2007 and 2020 years?

H0: There is no significant difference between mean TOPLAM_YARDIM of 2007 and 2020 years.

H1: There is significant difference between mean TOPLAM_YARDIM of 2007 and 2020 years.

# Before normalizing
t.test(mydata$TOPLAM_YARDIM[mydata$YIL==2007],mydata$TOPLAM_YARDIM[mydata$YIL==2020], data = mydata, var.equal = TRUE)  #p-value = 0.1667 > 0.05 fail to reject
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mydata$TOPLAM_YARDIM[mydata$YIL == 2007] and mydata$TOPLAM_YARDIM[mydata$YIL == 2020]
## t = -1.4381, df = 19, p-value = 0.1667
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -116629.22   21633.33
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  102611.8  150109.8
# After log transformation
t.test(mydata$log_TOPLAM_YARDIM[mydata$YIL==2007],mydata$log_TOPLAM_YARDIM[mydata$YIL==2020], data = mydata, var.equal = TRUE)  #p-value = p-value = 0.5268 > 0.05 fail to reject
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mydata$log_TOPLAM_YARDIM[mydata$YIL == 2007] and mydata$log_TOPLAM_YARDIM[mydata$YIL == 2020]
## t = -0.64473, df = 19, p-value = 0.5268
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.5966966  0.3156582
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  11.52872  11.66924
# After Outlier and Log Transformation
t.test(new_data$log_TOPLAM_YARDIM[new_data$YIL==2007],new_data$log_TOPLAM_YARDIM[new_data$YIL==2020], data = new_data, var.equal = TRUE) #  p-value = 0.08165 > 0.05 fail to reject 
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  new_data$log_TOPLAM_YARDIM[new_data$YIL == 2007] and new_data$log_TOPLAM_YARDIM[new_data$YIL == 2020]
## t = -1.8508, df = 17, p-value = 0.08165
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.79004942  0.05166596
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  11.52872  11.89791

As I was curious about this hypothesis test, I applied 3 different t-tests using the formats of the data before normalization, after the log transform, and finally, the outliers were deleted. p value = 0.1667 before normalization p-value = 0.5268 after log transform p-value = 0.08165 after deleting the Outliers

Since every p-value here is greater than the significance level alpha, we fail in rejecting H0. Also, that the confidence interval value covers 0 shows that we will fail while rejecting H0. We can conclude that 2007 yearâs total help is not significantly different from 2020 yearâs average total help while p-value is greater than 0.05.

Finally, when we look at the three p-values ââhere, we see that we got the strongest result after the log transformation. However, the most normal state of the data was after the outliers were deleted, and I actually thought that the strongest result would be after the outliers were deleted. But then I realized that since the deleted data belongs to the year 2020, the t test with the data after the outliers were deleted gave lower results.

6.2 Is there a significant difference between the soups given in winter and summer?

H0: There is no significant difference between the soups given in winter and summer.

H1: There is significant difference between the soups given in winter and summer.

winter = subset(new_data, subset = new_data$AY == "12" | new_data$AY == "1" |  new_data$AY == "2" )
summer = subset(new_data, subset = new_data$AY == "6" | new_data$AY == "7" |  new_data$AY == "8" )
t.test(winter$VERILEN_CORBA_SAYISI,summer$VERILEN_CORBA_SAYISI, var.equal = TRUE) # p-value = 4.545e-07
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  winter$VERILEN_CORBA_SAYISI and summer$VERILEN_CORBA_SAYISI
## t = 5.4932, df = 80, p-value = 4.545e-07
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   4973.761 10624.824
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  8004.171   204.878

The p-value of the test is 4.545e-07, which is less than the significance level alpha = 0.05. We can reject H0, in other words the case that there is no significant difference between winter and summer with p-value 4.545e-07. In the box plot, which shows the soups given according to the months above, it can be easily seen that there is such a difference.

7 Anova Part - Dataset 1

7.1 Do the total number of aids change according to years?

H0: The total number of aids do not change according to years.

H0: Âµ1 = Âµ2 = Âµ3 = Âµ4 = Âµ5 = Âµ6 = Âµ7 = Âµ8 = Âµ9 = Âµ10 = Âµ11 = Âµ12 = Âµ13 = Âµ14

H1: The Âµi are not all equal.

First, letâs check if the data is categorical and draw a graph.

new_data$YIL = as.factor(new_data$YIL)
is.factor(new_data$YIL) #true
## [1] TRUE
ggplot(new_data, aes(YIL,TOPLAM_YARDIM))+geom_boxplot(aes(col=YIL))

Anova test: 

model1 = aov(new_data$TOPLAM_YARDIM ~ new_data$YIL)
summary(model1)
##               Df    Sum Sq   Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## new_data$YIL  13 5.753e+11 4.425e+10   31.76 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals    149 2.076e+11 1.393e+09                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

It was observed that the f-statistic was 31.76 and the corresponding p-value was quite significant since it was much less than the significance level. Therefore, it would be wise to reject the H0 hypothesis, which says that the total number of aids made in all years is equal. In other words, the total aid in 14 years is not equal. We apply the Tukey test to understand in which years there is a significant difference.

Tukey Test: With this test, we detect variables that differ significantly.

TukeyHSD(model1, conf.level = 0.95)

13 Hypothesis Tests - Dataset 2

13.1 Are there significant difference between mean log_Toplam.yardÄ±m.alan.Ã§ocuk.sayÄ±sÄ± of 2019 and 2020 years?

H0: There is no significant difference between mean log_Toplam.yardÄ±m.alan.Ã§ocuk.sayÄ±sÄ± of 2007 and 2020 years.

H1: There is significant difference between mean log_Toplam.yardÄ±m.alan.Ã§ocuk.sayÄ±sÄ± of 2007 and 2020 years.

t.test(new_data2$log_Toplam.yardÄ±m.alan.Ã§ocuk.sayÄ±sÄ±[new_data2$YÄ±l==2019],new_data2$log_Toplam.yardÄ±m.alan.Ã§ocuk.sayÄ±sÄ±[new_data2$YÄ±l==2020], data = new_data2, var.equal = TRUE) #  p-value = 0.2019 > 0.05 fail to reject 
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  new_data2$log_Toplam.yardÄ±m.alan.Ã§ocuk.sayÄ±sÄ±[new_data2$YÄ±l == 2019] and new_data2$log_Toplam.yardÄ±m.alan.Ã§ocuk.sayÄ±sÄ±[new_data2$YÄ±l == 2020]
## t = 1.3658, df = 10, p-value = 0.2019
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0

##  -0.4814496  2.0066074
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  3.127171  2.364593

The p-value of the test is 0.2019, which is more than the significance level alpha = 0.05. We can conclude that 2019âs average total number of children receiving assistance is not significantly different from 2020âs average total number of children receiving assistance with a p-value = 0.2019.

19 Hypothesis Tests - Dataset 3

19.1 Are there significant difference between mean BASVURU_ADEDI of 2019 and 2020 years?

H0: There is no significant difference between mean BASVURU_ADEDI of 2019 and 2020 years.

H1: There is significant difference between mean BASVURU_ADEDI of 2019 and 2020 years.

t.test(mydata3$log_BASVURU_ADEDI[mydata3$YIL == 2020], mydata3$log_BASVURU_ADEDI[mydata3$YIL == 2019], data = mydata3, var.equal = TRUE)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mydata3$log_BASVURU_ADEDI[mydata3$YIL == 2020] and mydata3$log_BASVURU_ADEDI[mydata3$YIL == 2019]
## t = 0.14327, df = 2865, p-value = 0.8861
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.1237683  0.1432808
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  1.478501  1.468744

The p-value of the test is 0.8861, which is more than the significance level alpha = 0.05. And it covers confidence interval 0. This means that there are cases where these two values are close to each other. That is, we fail while rejecting the H0 hypothesis. We can conclude that there is no difference between mean BASVURU_ADEDI of 2019 and 2020 years.

20 Anova Part - Dataset 3

20.1 Do the number of applications change according to years?

H0: The number of applications do not change according to years.

H0: Âµ1 = Âµ2 = Âµ3 = Âµ4 = Âµ5 = Âµ6 = Âµ7 = Âµ8 = Âµ9 = Âµ10

H1: The Âµi are not all equal.

We check if the data is categorical and plot a boxplot graph.

Since the data is categorical, we can do ANOVA.

Anova test: 

model3 = aov(mydata3$BASVURU_ADEDI ~ mydata3$YIL)
summary(model3)
##               Df    Sum Sq  Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## mydata3$YIL    9 1.321e+08 14682310   11.24 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals   9325 1.218e+10  1305723                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

It was observed that the f-statistic value was 13.14 and the corresponding p-value was much less than the significance level. Therefore, it would be wise to reject the H0 hypothesis, which states that the number of applications made in all years is equal. In other words, applications over 10 years are not equal. We apply the Tukey test to understand in which years there is a difference.

Tukey Test: With this test, we detect variables that differ significantly.

21 Discussion

Considering the effects of the pandemic on social actions,

- it was observed that there was no significant increase in the aid provided by the municipality during the pandemic period.

- it has been observed that children go to children and education centers less and there is no significant increase in the number of children receiving psychological support.

- it has been observed that the number of aid applications made during the pandemic period has increased.
